(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 12 :title "Chapter 12 — First-class continuations" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/12-first-class-continuations.md" :size 3740 :sha256 "0c290b8834c3c83a" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-12\ntitle: First-class continuations\nbook: reference\nchapter: 12\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [peirce]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 11-hygienic-macros\nnext: 13-the-fuel-budget\n---\n\n# Chapter 12 — First-class continuations\n\nThe wildest part of Scheme. Continuations turn *what happens next*\ninto a value you can hold and call.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A continuation is the rest of the computation, captured as a\n> function. Call it, and you resume from that point. It's how you\n> build exceptions, generators, coroutines, and — carefully —\n> backtracking.\n\n## The move — call/cc\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(+ 1 (call/cc\n       (lambda (k)\n         (+ 2 3))))\n;=> 6      ; k was never called; the continuation was ignored\n\n(+ 1 (call/cc\n       (lambda (k)\n         (k 10)\n         (+ 2 3))))\n;=> 11     ; k was called with 10; the (+ 2 3) never ran\n```\n\n`call/cc` takes a function. It calls that function with `k` — the\ncurrent continuation. `k` is *the rest of the computation from this\npoint*. Calling `k` with a value substitutes that value for the\nwhole call/cc expression.\n\nNote: Sakura Scheme does NOT support R5RS's full first-class\ncontinuations at all levels (see the R5 exclusion doctrine — R5\n`call/cc` etc. are outside her language). We support a bounded form\nsuitable for pattern-matched control flow — this chapter documents\nthe pattern.\n\n## The bounded pattern — `escape`\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define (find-first pred lst)\n  (escape (lambda (return)\n    (for-each\n      (lambda (x)\n        (when (pred x) (return x)))\n      lst)\n    #f)))\n\n(find-first even? '(1 3 5 4 7))    ;=> 4\n(find-first even? '(1 3 5 7))      ;=> #f\n```\n\n`escape` gives us a `return` we can call from inside the loop. When\ncalled, the whole `escape` expression finishes with that value.\n\n## Generators from `escape`\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define (make-counter)\n  (let ([n 0])\n    (lambda ()\n      (set! n (+ n 1))\n      n)))\n\n(define next (make-counter))\n(next)  ;=> 1\n(next)  ;=> 2\n(next)  ;=> 3\n```\n\nSimpler than full continuations — just a closure with state. Most\ngenerator use cases are covered.\n\n## Exceptions\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(define-syntax try\n  (syntax-rules (catch)\n    ((_ body ... (catch e handler-body ...))\n     (escape\n       (lambda (throw)\n         (with-exception-handler\n           (lambda (e) (throw (begin handler-body ...)))\n           (lambda () body ...)))))))\n\n(try\n  (/ 10 0)\n  (catch e (display \"caught\") 'error))\n;=> \"caught\"     side effect\n;=> 'error       return value\n```\n\nSame shape, wrapped in a macro. `throw` is our escape.\n\n## The infinite fixed-point trap\n\nContinuations make it easy to write programs that never terminate.\nThis is the paradox from Book of Words ch 17 (paradoxes):\n\n```sakura-scheme\n; DO NOT RUN — infinite fixed-point\n(define k #f)\n(+ 1 (call/cc (lambda (c) (set! k c) 0)))\n;=> 1\n\n(k 5)     ; resumes the (+ 1 _) with 5 — infinite loop of (+ 1 (k 5))\n```\n\nSakura Scheme's bounded form disallows this shape. `escape`\nexpressions can only be exited *within* their dynamic extent.\n\n## When to reach for it\n\n- Exception handling.\n- Early termination from a nested loop.\n- Simple generators via closures (not full CPS).\n\n## When not to\n\n- Anything requiring resumable multi-shot continuations. That's R5\n  territory. We don't do that.\n- \"Clever\" control-flow tricks that a straightforward function would\n  handle.\n\n## Cross-links\n\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 11 — hygienic macros (used for `try`).\n- [[book-of-reference]] ch 13 — the fuel budget (bounds continuations).\n- [[book-of-words]] ch 17 — paradoxes (the trap patterns).\n\n---\n\nTurn the page.\n")
